1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1398":"1398","1387":"1387","26 August 1428":"26 augustus 1428","1428":"1428","12 March 1387":"12 maart 1387","Wethersfield, Essex, England":"Wethersfield, Essex, England","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"12 March 1387–14 February 1436":"12 March 1387–14 February 1436","1385–1436":"1385–1436","1387–1436":"1387–1436","1398–1447":"1398–1447","1428–1483":"1428–1483","1366–1437":"1366–1437","1365–1426":"1365–1426","18 October 1426":"18 October 1426","before 1385":"before 1385","1385":"1385","1483":"1483","1426":"1426","1437":"1437","1447":"1447","1436":"1436","14 February 1436":"14 February 1436","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1398":"1398","1387":"1387","26 August 1428":"26 August 1428","1428":"1428","12 March 1387":"12 March 1387","Wethersfield, Essex, England":"Wethersfield, Essex, England","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Howard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the Middle English personal names <i>Huward</i> (also <i>Howard</i>) and <i>Heward</i>, from Old French <i>Huard</i> (itself from ancient Germanic <i>Hugihard</i>, <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, understanding, spirit’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, bold’). As <i>Hugh</i> appears in Middle English as both <i>How</i> and <i>Hew</i>, this is the definite origin of <i>Heward</i> and a source of <i>Howard</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. See   Hugh  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Haward</i> or <i>Howard</i>, usually an Anglicized form of Old Danish <i>Hāwarth</i> (Old Norse <i>Hávarthr</i>, from <i>há</i> ‘high’ + <i>varthr</i> ‘guard, guardian, warden’). Alternation between <i>Haward</i> and <i>Howard</i> may have led to later confusion with   Hayward  .","English: occasionally a variant of   Ewart   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Fogarty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, James Patrick, Kieran, Seamus, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Fógartaigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fógartach</i>’, a personal name from <i>fógartha</i> ‘proclaimed, banished, outlawed’. It is sometimes Anglicized as   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Huggard","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, from the medieval personal name <i>Hugard</i>, a variant of <i>Huard</i> (see   Howard  ). This surname is also established in Ireland (Kerry)."]},{"name":"Heward","meanings":["English: variant of   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Hayward","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>hayward</i> ‘keeper of the hedges and enclosures’ (Old English <i>hēgweard</i>), a manorial officer in charge of the common fields who protected corn and hay from cattle, theft, or damage, and supervised the harvest.","occasionally a variant of   Howard  ."]},{"name":"Huard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime, Adelard, Jacques, Jean-Pierre, Lucien, Marcel, Alcide, Amiee, Armand, Aurele, Clermont, Fernard.","French and Channel Islands (Jersey): from the Old French personal name <i>Huart</i>, either identical in origin with   Howard   1 or a pet form of Old French   Hue  .","History: Jean Huard from Courson-Monteloup in Essonne, France, married Anne-Marie Amiot in Quebec City, QC, in 1670."]},{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Howard of Wigenhall was born on 12 March 1387, in Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England, his father, Sir John Howard, was 21 and his mother, Lady Alice Tendering, was 22. He had at least 1 daughter with Mary Hussey. He died on 14 February 1436, in Wethersfield, Essex, England, at the age of 48, and was buried in Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"12 March 1387–14 February 1436":"12. märts 1387–14. veebruar 1436","1385–1436":"1385–1436","1387–1436":"1387–1436","1398–1447":"1398–1447","1428–1483":"1428–1483","1366–1437":"1366–1437","1365–1426":"1365–1426","18 October 1426":"18. oktoober 1426","before 1385":"enne 1385","1385":"1385","1483":"1483","1426":"1426","1437":"1437","1447":"1447","1436":"1436","14 February 1436":"14. veebruar 1436","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1398":"1398","1387":"1387","26 August 1428":"26. august 1428","1428":"1428","12 March 1387":"12. märts 1387","Wethersfield, Essex, England":"Wethersfield, Essex, England","Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Stoke by Nayland, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"12 March 1387–14 February 1436":"12. maaliskuuta 1387–14. helmikuuta 